Since parking functions stay above the main diagonal $y=x$, a natural statistic is given by counting the number of full cells between the main diagonal and the underlying path. This statistic is known as the ${\operatorname{area}}$. The parking function in Figure \ref{fig:pref} (the path on the left) has ${\operatorname{area}} = 5$. The other statistics used in the Shuffle Conjecture are less natural. They make use of the diagonals of the parking function - those cells cut by a single line of the form $y=x+k$. One is the word of a parking function $PF$, which is denoted $\sigma(PF)$. This is the permutation obtained by reading cars from highest to lowest diagonal and from right to left within each diagonal. The word of the parking function in Figure $\ref{fig:pref}$ is $4 \, 5 \, 3 \, 2 \, 1$. We will also make use of the descent set of the inverse of $\sigma$. This is the set of $i$ for which $i+1$ comes before $i$ in $\sigma$. For simplicity, we will denote this by ${\operatorname{ides}}(PF)$. In Figure $\ref{fig:pref}$, the parking function has ${\operatorname{ides}} = \{ 1, 2, 3 \}$.

The final statistic is ${\operatorname{dinv}}$, whose name is an abbreviation of diagonal inversion. There are two types of ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ for parking functions. A primary ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ occurs whenever two cars appear in the same diagonal and the car further left is smaller. In Figure \ref{fig:pref}, cars $1$ and $2$ form the only primary ${\operatorname{dinv}}$. A secondary ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ occurs whenever two cars appear in adjacent diagonals and the smaller car is both lower and further right. In Figure \ref{fig:pref}, cars $2$ and $3$ form the only secondary ${\operatorname{dinv}}$. The ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ of a parking function is the total number of primary and secondary ${\operatorname{dinv}}$s. Hence in Figure $\ref{fig:pref}$, ${\operatorname{dinv}}=2$. 

