The main result of this paper is a proof of Conjecture \ref{conj:sq}. In Section \ref{sec:sched}, we extend a notion of Haglund and Loehr \citep{HL05} and use it to enumerate, by ${\operatorname{area}}$ and ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ alone, those preference functions with given (fixed) cars in each diagonal. In Section \ref{sec:shift}, we will discuss the effects of shifting cars between diagonals on the enumeration we obtained in Section \ref{sec:sched}. This will allow us to relate the enumeration of preference functions by ${\operatorname{area}}$ and ${\operatorname{dinv}}$ to the enumeration of parking functions by ${\operatorname{area}}$ and ${\operatorname{dinv}}$. Finally, in Section \ref{sec:ides}, we will show how to use the results of Section \ref{sec:shift} to relate the full enumerations (using ${\operatorname{area}}$, ${\operatorname{dinv}}$, and ${\operatorname{ides}}$) of preference and parking functions. This, combined with a symmetric function identity and the Compositional Shuffle Conjecture, proves the Square Paths Conjecture.

In fact, we prove something much stronger: a relationship between the full enumerations of parking and preference functions with the same sets of cars in adjacent diagonals. This is analogous to Hicks' \citep{Athesis} conjectural refinement of the Compositional Shuffle Conjecture at the level of parking functions with fixed cars in diagonals. This suggests that there may be quasi-symmetric refinements for the symmetric functions sides of the Shuffle Conjecture and Square Paths Conjecture which correspond to these combinatorial enumerations.



